EngrMotivation: As an engineer, I wanted to continue learning the science and math which I found so engaging to learn in high school while developing the ability to apply abstract theories and concepts to the real world. It has always been a dream of mine to develop novel technology with widespread applications, and in engineering, I believe I will have the resources and networking available to accomplish just that.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Living a happy, active, and fulfilling life.
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Achieving financial independence to pursue my ideal lifestyle.
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Developing or contributing something to the world that will remain as my legacy.

EngrMotivation: I chose engineering because it cominbined my love for math and science. The idea of implementing the information I learn to make the world a better place, is a very apealing concept to me. I would love to apply my love for learning and knowledge to tasks that will make the future a brighter place.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Making the world a safer, happier place
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Being an expert in my field
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Creating a stable and comfortable life for myself and my loved ones

EngrMotivation: My motivation boils down to the fact that engineering focuses on applying math and science to solve real world problems. With solving real world problems comes the need for a very wide range of skills, making engineering, especially EngSci a very interdisciplinary field. The ability for me to learn these wide range of skills, and how they can be integrated into a practical application was the main motivating factor for me picking Engineering.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Making money
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Not being rejected by my family
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Telling people that their schedule isn't that bad

EngrMotivation: When I accepted my offer to engineering, it was because I liked the way engineering integrates mathematics and sciences in a way that works to solve problems.  I wanted to positively impact others, and engineering seemed like a way I could put my passions to good use.  However, my motivations have grown and deepened since then.  Now, I am motivated to experience the process of design, be creative and learn more about research.  In particular, I want to see the ways engineering pertains to fields like biology and medicine, and explore this area of research.  Coming to complete an undergraduate Engineering degree was a way I could build a breadth of knowledge that could help me if pursuing a career in academia or industry.  Thus, there was also a sizeable amount of indecisiveness that contributed to my decision, as contradictory as that may sound.  I loved the way the engineering skill set applies to a wide variety of careers within different fields.  As a whole, I am excited to grow through an undergraduate Engineering degree and do one of my favourite thingsâ€”learning.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Improving the lives of others in tangible ways
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making new discoveries, thus satisfying my curiosity and thirst for knowledge
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Experiencing new things

EngrMotivation:
My motivation to pursue a post-secondary education was reaffirmed this past year, during which I took a break from academics to go abroad independently and secure myself financially. During my travels and employment, I greatly missed the rigor of schoolwork and the stimulation that comes with an invigorating academic environment; although I pursued self-driven studies during this time, the lack of a like-minded community served to make the experience intellectually isolating rather than engaging. I prefer to be in situations where I am forced to reexamine myself and outgrow my limitations, despite feeling out of my depth at times-- once I'm comfortable in an environment, I no longer feel that I'm in the right place. While travelling and supporting myself did provide the opportunity to redraw some of my personal boundaries, I feel that the challenges presented by university offer the greatest potential for personal growth at this point in my life.
As for my choice of degree-- while my interests lie in the conceptual, I personally feel unfulfilled unless my actions have a direct, beneficial impact on the lives of others. I've always been interested in the interplay between theory and practice, especially regarding how we (humans) approach problems of all kinds (social, ethical, environmental, analytical, physical)-- Engineering Science ostensibly engages with this idea directly and therefore seemed like the most appealing program to me.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Being able to contribute to the world in a way that directly benefits individuals
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Personal growth (self-awareness, personal understanding, enlightenment, fulfillment)
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Defying expectations (internal and external)

EngrMotivation: My father is a Chemical Engineer working in oil and gas in Alberta so being influenced by an engineer has been very prominent in my life. I had no intention of becoming a chemical engineer, but the variety and exposure that the engineering offers as a discipline was very intriguing. Although other paths such as pursuing literature or science would be really interesting to learn about with immediate access to electives in various fields no other option offered the ability to have such a concrete impact on society as much an becoming an engineer.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Self-fulfillment
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making my parents sacrifices worth it and surpassing their expectations
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Solving problems in a variety of areas, and having a lasting impact with my thoughts

EngrMotivation: Engineering offers the most tangible application of complex ideas and advanced knowledge into the real world. The disconnect present in other programs would make me feel like what I have learned is not applicable in the improving of society and the solving problems that humans are faced with. I wanted to better understand the concepts I could apply before using them so getting an undergraduate degree and possibly a masters would allow me to use a much broader and deeper understanding in whatever field I end up in whether that be research or the work force.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Gaining understanding of the world around me and using it to better the world around me
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Having a secure job due to a high level of education (hopefully) so I can live in comfort
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Providing for and being able to have a family

EngrMotivation: I have always loved science and problem-solving. As a very diligent person with great critical-thinking abilities, I believe I am very fit to be an engineer. In addition, I thought that engineering would be a lot of fun. This field of study is essential for the survival of a community as engineers come up with solutions to difficult problems and have a significant impact on our daily lives.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Learning fun things and being great at them
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Being a unique person
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Receiving a lot of respect

EngrMotivation: I am interested in utilizing my scientific knowledge to improve the lives around me. I love the fundamentals of science but I am more exciting to learn science and the application of science  to help people other than just for my own intrinsic gain.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: making myself proud, by feeling I have fulfilled my potential
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: making my family proud
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: making money to travel

EngrMotivation:
In high school, I enjoyed learning mathematics and physics more than any other school subjects. Therefore, I thought choosing a major that is closely related to mathematics and physics would suit my learning interests.

I aspire to become an entrepreneur in the technology industry, to create solutions that address shortcomings in the society. I believe that an important quality for me to have is to have a solid understanding in related  technologies. It will allow me to truly oversee both business and R&D sides of the company. In addition, the analytical approach and problem-solving skills that I will obtain as an engineering student will benefit me to manage and grow my business.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Making something that benefits the society
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Leading and educating other people
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Having the freedom and capability to pursue my personal dreams

DontCallJusticiation: I prefer to participate in open team/group discussions and input when I have something meaningful to contribute. That said, I don't find it too uncomfortable to be called upon directly.
EngrMotivation: I actually really like chemistry, but overall science and math in general. I thought engineering was a more realistic (I guess) way of using those skills, basically applying them to solve problems that are actually present. I also like music and the arts but I didn't think I was "good enough" at it to be in a program. I thought of those more as hobbies than something I wanted to spend my time pursuing through a degree. I chose an undergrad degree because I believe that it is a necessity if I want to become an engineer in the future.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Helping other people through solving their issues/problems
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making enough money to give back to my family and start my own family
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Being able to pursue something that'll make me happy

EngrMotivation:
I've loved math and science for as long as I can remember, and I have always been curious about the natural world and its order. I read as many books about science as I could get my hands on and always questioned the world around me. I recall asking my dad when I was quite young: "Why don't rocks jump off of the ground?" My family also has a strong background in science, which further motivated me. I also learned that I love to think about problems and create novel solutions to those problems. As well, I enjoy taking challenges. Finally, I wanted to make a meaningful difference in the world through the combination of all of the above characteristics. However, it took a long time before I realized that an undergraduate degree in engineering was best suited for me.

Initially, I thought about taking a pure science university program, but I eventually realized that while some sciences would allow you to apply what you learn to real-life scenarios (such as food science), many other programs were more geared towards research with few chances to apply your knowledge to help others.
In addition, I had seriously considered pursuing music at university, which is one of my greatest passions. However, my desire to tackle global issues through applied science and engineering won out, and I decided to continue music as a hobby.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Contribute meaningfully to society and making an impact
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making a decent living to support myself and my family
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Enjoying life to the fullest

EngrMotivation: Engineering for me represents opportunity. During my application process, once thing that constantly deterred me from other fields of studies was the lack of range and depth covered in each of the courses they offered. I wanted to be able to be well educated in all aspects of learning. I don't believe certain subjects are more important than others (ex. physics over biology), but rather believe that an understanding of all subjects is what creates well rounded students capable of tackling all sorts of problems. This, in the end, is what drew me to engineering (or eng sci in particular). I want to be able to come out of this program with a well rounded knowledge set, so I know that in the future, I'll have the tools to tackle what ever problems are thrown at me. If I could live on this earth forever, I'd try and learn everything the world has to offer, and use that knowledge to 1. solve the most unreachable problems, 2. push innovation to its limits, and 3. help my community become the best place it could possibly be. I feel like engineering is the closest I can get to that in the short amount of time I have, and that, therefore, is the motivation that has pushed me into choosing engineering as my undergraduate degree.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Making a impact that will be remembered (and helpful)
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Stability (in finances, friendships, etc...) so I have a strong foundation upon which I can pursue my dreams
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Making others proud, happier, etc... (family, friends, teachers, strangers)

EngrMotivation:
I chose to pursue an Engineering degree because of:
a) My passion for technology: I've always had a strong interest in computers and the tech industry. I wanted to study the process of designing and building these products as well as the technical knowledge behind them.
b) Practicality and my preference for hands-on learning: I'm a tinkerer, and engineering allows me to use practical skills and my creativity to actually build things that will have practical benefits. I very much prefer this over another more theory-heavy program, say, Computer Science.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: The process of creating something original that I could be proud of and that other people could enjoy / benefit from
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Helping others through various means - explaining a concept, technical support, give directions, building a product, etc.
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Having financial security

EngrMotivation: I am motivated my engineering for several reasons. Firstly, I have a strong desire to learn, and I will get a chance to be a life long learner in Engineering. In particular, I have a passion for math and physics, which is the basic theory than an engineer uses to solve problems. I am looking forward to getting a chance to be creative and make new designs. I am interested in trying new things, and solving questions different ways. I think that working together is an effective way to solve a problem. I like being challenged by others, and building off of other people's ideas to solve problems effectively. I am still unsure of which engineering field I wish to pursue, so I choose engineering science. I think it is a great program because I will be exposed to different areas in engineering in the first two years, and it gives me many possibilities for my future.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: being challenged by others, encouraging me to grow
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: forming good habits
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: helping others reach their full potential

EngrMotivation: I really like math, science and problem solving. Learning more knowledge makes me happy and fulfilled. In the meantime, I want to showcase my knowledge, and help people do better in their lives. Engineers contribute to the development of the world in a very meaningful way, and they are often fearless of their challenges and do not fall from their mistakes. That's what motivates me to be an engineer -- to pioneer in a specific area and let people enjoy the benefits of it. Personally I am not the most hand-on person either, but I am passionate about learning to be practical and collaborative, and even a become a good leader.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Learning to use tools and build things in a more efficient way
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Plan my university life well so that I can enjoy my life with friends, excel in academics and extra-curriculars while not spending too much money
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Making others comfortable, safe and respected around me

EngrMotivation:
The reason I chose engineering over other paths, is because I like the idea of learning a mindset that can be used to develop and learn new skills, rather than just memorizing a set of skills that accomplish one particular thing. Of all the engineers I know, a lot of them have been able to work in areas outside of their own expertise, because they posses that ability to learn new skills without being explicitly taught them. 

Along with that flexibility, the other reason I chose engineering is because I think my generation is going to have some big environmental problems to deal with in the next few decades, and I want to be able to do something to help solve (or minimize) the consequences  of those problems. 
Being able to think in a way that not a lot of people can (and being able to apply this to ALL aspects of life)
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Being able to think in a way that not a lot of people can (and being able to apply this to ALL aspects of life)
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Having the ability to make a broader impact (preferably for the better)
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Being able to work in a variety of environments and jobs

EngrMotivation:
I chose an undergraduate degree in Engineering because I wanted an undergraduate experience that was intellectually stimulating and appealed to my interests in the maths and sciences. I felt that the technical knowledge that I will gain in an undergraduate engineering degree will help increase my potential to succeed in employment and entrepreneurship as opposed to directly entering the workforce. Moreover, I also chose to pursue engineering studies because of the rigour of the curriculum; I do not like being bored and having lots of idle time. 

Furthermore, as opposed to other programs that would have interested me such as music, the humanities, and the natural sciences, an undergraduate degree in engineering will provide me with a stable base to continue my career in many ways. I could choose to pursue a career in industry and try to obtain job stability or I could pursue graduate studies. Furthermore, an engineering degree, as opposed to many other degrees, will allow me to access more lucrative jobs.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Learning as much as I can in 4 years
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Flexibility upon graduation
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Financial stability once I decide to go into employment

EngrMotivation: I chose Engineering because it is a discipline that uses a variety of tools such as math and physics in order to solve problems on a large scale. What appealed to me was the fact that engineers must implement these tools into their designs, rather than learning for the sake of learning.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Being able to have input and involvement in large scale projects
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making a comfortable living
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Designing projects and doing research that can benefit the world

EngrMotivation: I actually wanted to do a degree in English ever since I was younger, because I wanted to write books and be a storyteller. Turns out, however, that I'm decent at the sciences and maths too. I've always had a curiosity to know how the universe works and how we, as people, fit into it. That's one of the many things engineering and English have in common. You get to learn about the world as we know it and how we fit into it; how to make all the pieces fit together. Engineering Science does a good job of giving you that breadth of knowledge and experience. I did this course, and all of the semester last year and unfortunately had to drop it mid-way into the semester due to an injury, but when I entered I was unsure if this was what I wanted to do. Coming back to it, I know it's something I want to do.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Being someone in a grand universe
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Getting to do exciting things and experiencing as much as I can in my life
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: My support system

EngrMotivation: During elementary school, my "dream job" was to be an Inventor.  When I found out that universities don't offer a degree for Inventors, I discovered Engineering! Upon further research into engineering programs, I realized that pursing a degree (and subsequently a career) in Engineering is the perfect way for me to use my skills and interest in mathematics and applied science. I hope following this path will allow me to design, innovate and invent technology for the betterment society.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Doing something meaningful with my career
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Maintaining my personal values/morals
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Personal improvement that ultimately benefits others

DontCallJusticiation: At times, it takes me more time to thoroughly think of an answer. Also, I  would usually volunteer if I have something to say, so if I do not volunteer, that means I do not have something to say. Other times, I genuinely want to hear other people's opinions or answers.
EngrMotivation: I find myself to be a very logical person however I have a strong drive to create and invent, specifically to help others in the world and feel that I am making a positive impact and actually being useful to the world. University was the only path that would unlock such opportunities to create or invent an item that pertain to my scientific interests.  I choose engineering instead of other sciences because of its practicality, as well as the creativity behind it, which is not easily found in other science based courses.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Security (financially and emotionally)
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Maintaining a balance between different aspects of life (ie. school, family) to acheieve happiness.
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Fulfilling a need of self worth through gaining knowledge and skills.

EngrMotivation: I went to a school with a frenhch system, so in grade 11 we had to choose between engineering, biology, economics and litterature. I chose engineering mostly because none of the other options appealed to me. As for why I chose engineering in university, I believe an engineering degree gives me the possibility to choose my own path, I still don't know what my passion is, or what I want to do for a living, but an engineering degree gives me a way of thinking I can use in whatever I choose to do later on.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: being happy
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: making enough money to be healthy and support my family
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: sharing memories with friends and family

EngrMotivation: I chose an undergraduate degree in engineering so I both learn the theoretical side of math, chemistry and physics at a higher level and explore the applications of this knowledge. Both my parents also have a background in applied science and engineering as my father is an electrical engineer and my mother completed her undergraduate degree in infrastructure management so they persuaded me to also choose an undergraduate degree in engineering.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: A career in academia
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Living life to the fullest
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: My friends and family

EngrMotivation: I knew that I wanted to pursue a degree in Engineering because I would like to eventually find a career where I can creatively solve problems while using technical skills in science and math. Throughout high school, my science classes were always my favorite as I enjoy learning about how the world around me works and how we can use that knowledge to create things and solve problems. I chose  an Engineering degree over a degree in math or science because I want to learn more practical and hands on skills that I can apply to any work I do.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Doing things that I know are making people's lives better
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Knowing more about the way the world  fundamentally works and operates
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Being able to create something that I can be proud of afterward

EngrMotivation: There are many reasons why I chose an undergraduate degree in Engineering over all of the other paths. I've always had a strong aptitude for math and physics, but I've also always wanted to be able to apply that knowledge to the "real world." I want to design things that improve the lives of other people. I also really like the fact that engineering is only a four year degree versus going to medical school after a science degree for example. Most undergrad programs require you to study something afterwards whether it be a Masters degree or any other graduate program to get a well paying job, but engineering doesn't require it.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Being able to use my knowledge of math and physics to design things that improve the lives of others
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Well paying
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Length of study period

DontCallJusticiation: In a larger room with more people I sometimes get a bit uncomfortable and usually prefer to listen
EngrMotivation: In high school I was interested in business, technology, math and science. I started to take all of the business and technology courses available to me, but the more business I took, the less interested I became and started focusing more on technology. My favorite courses were the math, science and technology courses such as computer science and computer engineering, and I especially liked designing and creating a solution to somewhat challenging problems and working hands-on.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Understanding how to apply knowledge in useful ways to solve problems
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: learning new skills that can be applied in many ways
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: getting a good job and making enough money to pursue my dreams

EngrMotivation: I really enjoy building and designing projects with other people. I would rather get my hands dirty and create new things rather than studying in theoretical fields such as physics or mathematics. I am not a very creative or abstract-thinking person. I tend to be more technical and practical. My parents were both engineers and they loved their studies in university. My dad initially discouraged me from going into engineering as I "never disassembled and reassembled a bike" before. However, I knew that engineering would be a better fit for me.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Improving from my mistakes
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: To set the best example for my little sister
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Making other people happy

EngrMotivation: Engineering has been something I have been interested in pursuing from a very young age and particularly contributing to the effort of space exploration through aerospace engineering has been what I have wanted to do for the past 5 years or so. With that in mind, no other path or program would have made sense for me to pursue.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Contributing to human knowledge
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Helping other people
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Understanding things that have confused me before

DontCallJusticiation: I feel as if I am quicker to understand subjects when I observe firstly. After I am more comfortable with the subject, I tend to find it easier to be called on directly.
EngrMotivation: I want to become an astronautical engineer. I believe that space exploration is incredibly important for our future. I hope to one day work on new propulsion systems that can take us further than ever before.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Ensuring I get an engineering degree to help me play a part in the future of space exploration
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making enough money to support my parents and let them live without stress
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: The idea of being able to work in a job that I will never get tired off

EngrMotivation: I chose to take an undergrad in engineering as I feel it is a degree that directly allows for creative and innovative thought - even prior to graduation. It is a dynamic and changing field which consistently provides new opportunities to learn and broaden your perspective. There is huge cultural diversity, passion, and varied interest, within the engineering community which allows for constant development, adaptation, and innovation within the industry and also allows the influence of engineers to bleed into all aspects of society. Healthcare, transport, infrastructure, entertainment, all are impacted by the engineering community. This degree promises choices, possibilities, and lifelong learning. It promises interaction and collaboration with minds different than your own to create something that could create real change within society. Who could say no to that?
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: undying curiosity
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: intrinsic motivation to push my limits
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: my little sister

EngrMotivation: Engineering offers something unique, the opportunity to dive in to the depths of theory; while incorporating these abstract concept into daily practices. This degree will equip me with the necessary skills needed for further studies in Academia after my undergraduate years.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Learning as much information as possible
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Being able to enter Graduate studies
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Fully utilizing my tuition

EngrMotivation: The most prominent reason I had for choosing this program was the options it gave me. Unlike the other option I was considering of studying to become a drama teacher, Engineering science gave me the opportunity to transfer out to other institutes or disciplines more easily. It allowed me to test out engineering and see if it tailored to me likes and ideal lifestyles. I am also intrigued by the science of the world; the how and the why of everything, and engineering science seemed to offer a more rigorous and deep dive into those concept. More importantly though, it relates those concepts to the real world and to how we can apply them. I do still greatly enjoy drama and theater arts in general, but as my drama teacher told me "You can be an actor anywhere, but you can't be an engineer anywhere".
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: The positive impact my work can have on the  world
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: The knowledge I will gain
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: The people I will be surrounded by

EngrMotivation: Besides being generally interested in engineering (see  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6aQlbqHZuYk ), I was motivated to enter Engineering Science because it provides the most options given my well-established interest in math and physics. I can graduate and find a job in a field I'm pretty sure I will like, or continue to grad school after I've refined my interests a bit, or even switch into a more specific STEM field during my degree. Engineering seemed like the most practical and most convenient choice given my interests and goals.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Access to a wide variety of careers and study involving math and problem solving
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: The ability to have a positive influence on the world
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: (Hopefully) decent money

EngrMotivation: An engineering degree was very compelling to me for many; it offered the opportunity to do something I thoroughly enjoy - theoretical learning, but also learn practical application that I can build upon to contribute back to doing something positive for the world and community around me. I saw engineering as the best and most flexible path to follow, especially in EngSci, as it gives me the freedom to pick my own path after 2 years of gaining university experience and understanding what is the correct fit for my goals.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Opportunity to Learn and Innovate
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Self Accomplishment
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Financial Security

EngrMotivation: I'm really interested in biomedicine, and I know engsci is a great place to learn. In the engineering program, I can learn how to apply the knowledge to the real life. I want to make some contributions to biomedicine, and I think the application of knowledge is the most important part.  I consider choosing an undergraduate degree in Engineering as a useful and essential path to my future career.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: understanding more about the world
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: knowing things that few other people do
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: making enough money for me and my family

EngrMotivation: I originally wanted a more theoretical degree like something in pure mathematics or physics, but I thought that it would be better to have practical applications for my degree. I chose a university degree because it was the expectations of my family and I hadn't really considered anything else.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Seeing something work that I made/built
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Seeing someone understand a concept once I have explained it
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Meeting new people

EngrMotivation:
I knew that an undergraduate degree was the path that I wanted to pursue because I've always wanted the experience and knowledge that comes with going to university and getting a degree. Plus, both my parents went to university for undergraduate and graduate degrees, so they have instilled a sense of value and emphasis on higher education in me. 
As for choosing an Engineering program, that was also not a hard choice for me, and it was one I did with a good amount of certainty. I've been interested in aerospace since I was 10, and that's when I began saying that I wanted to be an aerospace engineer when I grew up. Since then, various experiences have furthered my interest, especially discussions with a family friend who's an engineer at Jet Propulsion Laboratory and receiving tours of JPL from him. The one other subject that I considered studying is Photography, and I even applied for a dual degree program in the two subjects at another school. Ultimately, I chose Engineering because I can see myself getting more lifelong fulfillment with a career in Engineering than I could with one in Photography.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Finding my ideal, authentic self and doing what it takes to be that
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Reaching my long-term career goal
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Wanting to do something with my life that I'm proud of

EngrMotivation:
I have this crazy dream of someday being part of a team that invents a way to effectively synthesize customized artificial organs. There are too many people in the world stuck on transplant lists waiting for a lifesaving organs; many of whom will die still waiting. 

I suppose I could have just gone directly into a biomedical sciences school/program, but I think having an engineering foundation will allow me to better bridge multiple disciplines of STEM for example tissue biology with 3D printing. Organs can really be broken down and classified into individual parts of a mechanical system each working in tandem to sustain the perpetually active machine that is the organ.

Research are so incredibly close to a breakthrough in this endeavour, and I'd love to contribute someday to the cause.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: To help create artificial organs for transplant patients
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Helping my fellow female peers succeed in male-dominated STEM fields
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Become financially independent to pay back my family for financing my education

EngrMotivation: I though an engineering degree was the best possible was for me to have success and enjoyment throughout and after my undergraduate experience. Engineering excites me because I really want to be able to develop my ability to problem solve, thing critically, and work under pressure while studying courses I enjoy. I am specifically motivated by the statistics/mathematics/ finance option because in High School, statistics was by far my favorite course and I enjoy being able to apply  and make connections between the classroom and the outside world.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Feeling mentally competent while talking to very smart people.
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Knowing that this atmosphere will help me handle stress and balance efficiently
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Being innovative to help others

DontCallJusticiation: It often takes me time to come up with an answer. If I am called upon directly, I often get very nervous and I am either not able to answer the question or do not answer to the best of my ability.
EngrMotivation: I found interest in Engineering after I had successfully built a drone in Grade 9 from scratch, which I thought to be pretty cool. The process of building the drone involved both programming, math as well as designing which I found to be something I enjoyed doing. Pursuing Engineering was my choice because it would allow me to build on these interests, while making my post secondary education enjoyable. It is also my parents wish for me to pursue Engineering so everything worked out. I chose this path because I wanted to study Engineering at a renowned and reputable institution before heading into the workforce.

Additionally, the chance to become a part of the constant effort to understand and explore space was a motivating factor. I chose to become an engineer over anything else because I saw it as the best way to both incorporate my existing soft skills as a communicator and creative-thinker with my hard skills and passion for studying science, technology, and mathematics. Studying engineering would be a way for me to use all of my skills together while refining them with the right mindset. 

EngSci is a difficult major and I took it up because I have the drive to take on such endeavors to challenge and push myself to become both well-rounded and highly skilled in certain areas so I can maximise my abilities as an engineer in the future.

Since I want to pursue aerospace engineering, I was somewhat limited in the options I had for post-graduate studies. All major aerospace-oriented companies (such as NASA, ESA, etc.), as well as minor aerospace-oriented companies, require a degree in aerospace or mechanical engineering. Furthermore, a graduate degree significantly increases the chances of employment in the aerospace industry. Therefore, to reach my goal, my best option was to come to an aerospace/mechanical engineering program where I could learn a lot as well as get the opportunity to get some in-field experience.

To me, engineering has a higher expectation for "hard skills" and law, although contains much content, requires more "soft skills". If I have something interesting I'd like to contribute, I will try my best to share it, but putting me on the spot unexpectedly will probably cause a minor panic attack followed by a jumble of words.
EngrMotivation:
I really liked the fact that an engineering education teaches you to think in a certain way that is not taught in other undergraduate degree programs - engineers are taught to solve complex problems that involve a wide range of factors and consequences - a skill that is in very high demand, is applicable to almost any other professional field, and is not often taught rigorously in other disciplines. The employment numbers for an engineer aren't too bad either ;)
However, engineering is a professional degree for a reason - it is meant to prepare students for the workplace straight after university (very practical). Unfortunately, my thought process does tend to be more theoretical, and I find theories to be much more interesting than concrete information (wow, after reading what I just wrote maybe pure science really is a better match for me, lol). Anyways, EngSci was a nice option that sufficiently combined both theory and practice: I would be able to pursue the theory-based learning I desired, and at the same time sharpen my practical reasoning skills. Unfortunately the workload is apparently killer, and it turns out my grit score isn't the best... :/

GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Successfully accomplishing a long-term goal
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Knowing things that few other people do

More specifically, the EngSci program is just as hard and new to me as it is interesting, and full of courses that teach you how to apply your skills and relate them to each other. GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: My inventions positively impacting the world at large (Is equal to the most motivating)

I chose engineering because I want to contribute to the growth of our world
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Being financially successful and independent
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Doing things that I never knew I could do
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Finding happiness

EngrMotivation:
I chose to do an undergraduate degree because my culture's expectation for high school grads is to proceed to university and get a degree. I have never questioned this notion and thus have never considered other options. In retrospect, the basis of this life decision sounds weak; however, I genuinely like school, so I want to continue to pursue academics, and university is where I can do that.

I am interested in math, science, visual and digital art, and literature. However, I elected STEM courses over art courses in high school, as STEM programs have strict prerequisites while art programs are more flexible. This action eventually lead me to decide on pursuing STEM post-secondary, because the more I learn about STEM, the more eager I am to learn more. Employment and financial security is also an important factor in my decision to pursue engineering. My family exhausted most of their financial resources to immigrate to Canada, and as a result, I need to earn decent money for my family to really settle in this country, so that my younger siblings can chase their dreams. Plus, as I learn about engineering, I grew to like the profession, its social responsibility, and the engineer identity. I can envision myself enjoying my career as an engineer one day.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Learning interesting topics/ideas/skills, mastering them, and coming up with my own
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Feeling fulfilled (spiritually, academically, socially, emotionally, etc.)
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Making enough money  (to lighten up the financial burden on my parents, to help others, and to afford a house in Toronto XD)

EngrMotivation: I chose an undergraduate degree in Engineering because I have a strong interest in physics and in applying it. EngrMotivation:
I think perhaps this explanation will sound strange, since I openly say that math and science were not, in fact, my favourite subjects in school. At that point in the conversation, most people ask me why I'm in Engineering Science. But it's true, I didn't choose engineering because I fell in love with STEM. Rather, I chose engineering because, as idealistic as it may sound, I want to change the world. When I think of what I want to do for the rest of my life, I don't want to sit in an office or at a cubicle all day. I picked Engineering because I know that it opens doors, that Engineering is a vast and diverse field that is constantly changing and pushing the boundaries, and I especially chose Engineering Science because it focuses on those groundbreaking fields. 
You asked us in our very first lecture whether engineers should be involved in public policy. I thought it was amusing, since I'm actually considering going into public policy after Engineering, which is probably why my table ended up being the "Strong Yes" table. I know it's a somewhat unconventional choice, but I do believe that an undergraduate degree in Engineering, especially one that challenges and pushes its students to the degree that Engineering Science does, is something that brings new and much-needed perspective to public policy.

GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Helping others
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: To be remembered

EngrMotivation:
I was motivated to apply for an undergraduate degree in Engineering because of the job stability and employment opportunities that are available compared to other fields. I really want to have experience working in a foreign country as I enjoy travelling and I feel that engineering is a global pursuit that could guide me towards this goal. The salaries of engineers also interested me as the starting salary for engineers is higher than for other programs. A big motivation for completing an engineering undergrad was the lack of need for completing further education as one can enter the industry after completing their undergraduate degree. Additionally, I enjoy the fact that engineering can be applied to be more artistic fields such as the cosmetics industry. It has the ability to be applied to many fields making it a great backup for any job or further education. 
I chose to do engineering over other paths as I wanted to continue to expand my scientific knowledge and innovation. Additionally, I feel that the other pathways can still be explored later in life without set back or consequences. Whereas to immediately gain an entry level industry position one needs a degree and it would be beneficial to have one earlier. 
I chose engineering over other programs because of the opportunities it provides over other programs and degrees as I outlined above. As well, i felt engineering encapsulated many of my strengths, which couldn't have been possible in a regular arts and science degree, as I felt I would've sacrificed creativity or scientific pursuit.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Global and stable employment opportunities
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Money
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Opportunity to work in various fields

EngrMotivation: When I was 7, my brother was born very prematurely (only 6 months into the pregnancy). I started to see all the different machines that were used to help him and my mom and I realized how much I wanted to create those machines myself.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Knowing that one day I will be able to help other families like mine years ago
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Being able to design and create new things
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Showing the world those designs

EngrMotivation: Personally, I have always had an interest in creating complex programs that manage to do multiple things at once. It also helps that I am very interested in Math and the principles of physics. Altogether, I felt that the best way to integrate all those interests would be to join Engineering.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Making enough money in the future to live a lavish lifestyle.
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: To make a family of my own in addition to my existing one.
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: To be successful in the pursuits that I take.

EngrMotivation: I would like to have my own company in the future. My plan is to have some kinds of innovation and build a start-up for it. In this case, I believe EngSci can provide me with a firm base for my career path. I can meet people in this field and have ideas in mind that will assist me.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Have my own innovation
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Have economic capability to do what I want to do.
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: be considered as successful/ intelligent

EngrMotivation: My decision of pursuing Engineering was very recent. I realised that an undergraduate degree in Engineering would come with exciting challenges and a pressure of thinking innovatively to solve arising problems. Engineering is quite practical and realistic. This tends to connect me more to, and make me aware of, my surroundings. It really gives me the opportunity to have a role in every aspect of the modern world.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Possessing something that others do not
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Earning enough money/recognition to fulfil my dreams
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Bringing out the best in everyone to create a problem-free world

EngrMotivation: I chose to pursue a degree in engineering at UofT instead of a degree in engineering at McGill or a degree in economics at UofT or Mcgill because I felt that the Engineering Science would allow me to explore several different fields of engineering allowing me to make a more informed decision about what field I would study in, as well as providing me with an understanding in several different fields in engineering which could be valuable in future pursuits regardless of what I specialize in. I chose engineering over economics because I felt that the skills learnt in an engineering program are more adaptable and marketable as compared to economics. I can always choose to focus on a different field after engineering but I think it is much harder to focus on engineering after studying economics.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Being better than others
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Seeing tangible results
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: The feeling you get after solving a problem that has stumped you for a long time

EngrMotivation: I chose engineering because I love math and science and I like the idea of being able to grow my knowledge in the fields and use what I have learned to directly improve the lives of others. I felt that this would be easier to connect with people and develop things specifically for them more through an engineering pathway than through one in science. I feel that going to university would allow to to grow my knowledge of concepts and also develop a good work ethic that I could take into the real world more than any other option like college or going straight into the workforce.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Being able to use my privileges and give back to improve the quality of life for others
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Being able to be innovative and discover new ways of doing things
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Being able to live comfortably and be happy and not stressed all the time

EngrMotivation: I want to learn advanced math and programming that will further develop my critical thinking skills, helping me achieve my goal of being an incredible programmer.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Support from others
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Improving at something
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: End goal

EngrMotivation:
There are many small-scale reasons for which I chose engineering. These include my enjoyment of math and science, as well as my past success with engineering-type projects. But, there is one reason for my choosing engineering that lies at the center of my decision. 

Essentially, one of my main goals in life is to have as much of a positive impact on the world as possible, and I strongly believe in the power of well-used science and technology to improve the vast majority of situations. Based on my experience, I seem to have some aptitude for engineering and its related fields, and, more importantly, I have universally enjoyed my experiences with said fields of study. Though there are other fields that I have enjoyed and seemed to have some aptitude for, I believe that I will have the greatest probability of success in my goal if I study engineering because I have seen what is possible when science, technology, and effective problem-solvers are brought together in the right way.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Creating innovative things that help people in novel and effective ways
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Increasing the number and the effectiveness of the tools that I have at my disposal (cognitive and physical) to further my first motivation
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Understanding the way that the world works

EngrMotivation: I chose to study an undergraduate degree in Engineering by attending a university since I was unsure of whether I would thrive choosing other pathways (e.g. employment, entrepreneurship, college, etc.). University felt the most secure and safe path to follow through for now due to the high reputation that the University of Toronto offers and the fact that I am still not 100 percent sure of what I want to do in the future. I was unsure of whether I wanted to choose life sciences  or engineering as my program choice, but I eventually made the decision of choosing engineering. I do not have a lot of preference in terms of the content in these two very different program choices. The reason I chose engineering over life science was because although I was fairly confident that I would be accepted into medical school, I still knew there would be a risk factor going down that path if I had not gotten accepted into medical school. I was not confident of being superior over others in the field of medicine. However, I have always been able to confidently express myself better than most others in engineering related courses.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Living a healthy life
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making enough money that I can
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Having time to spend time with my family

EngrMotivation: I enjoy math and science and working to solve existing real life problems. I feel engineering would fit me the best, as there is a strong focus on my interested subjects, as well as having the opportunity to do hands-on works at the lab.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Making an impact on the society by solving urgent issues
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Meeting new people and broadening my perspectives
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Making money to support family

EngrMotivation: I chose engineering over all the other programs available to me because of my large interest in both Mathematics and Physics. Engineering would give me the chance to apply my skills in both these subjects into trying to create innovative machines and design that could have global impacts. Engineering also offers me a wide range of employment opportunities that would give me a base to express all the skills I develop throughout the course. Enrolling myself into an Engineering program was my preferred choice over options such as employment as I was prepared to undergo such a testing course knowing that in four years my curiosity on how everything works would be fulfilled. Besides that, I would be able to use my specialized skills obtaining in trying to create new inventions.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Analyzing and visualizing my future goals
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Understanding the effort of my parents to provide me with an easy up-bringing
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Monetary success

DontCallJusticiation: I get very self conscience
EngrMotivation:
Honestly. I would have preferred to start working as I need to develop a more mature mentality towards the struggles of everyday life. However, further pursuing my education is vital for me to succeed in life which for me is my ultimate goal. 
I have always loved the concept of school; learning new concepts and what not. Sadly, i 'run out of steam' often and need a recharge once in a while. 
When i have the energy i am constantly intrigued by the way things work and how they work in that specific manner. Which can be explained after i take engineering science.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: helping others succeed
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: overcoming my own personal hurdles
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Becoming stable monetary wise.

EngrMotivation: This Engineering Degree was a perfect mix of meeting my passions, while also having a large scope for employment once I graduated. I love how Engineering Science mixes both the logical--courses like calculus and computer science, where there is a clear set of steps necessary to arrive at an answer--and the creative--courses like Praxis, where more than anything, you must be creative to think of novel approaches. In addition to the learning experience being enjoyable, I would also be able to apply them in a real-world setting in a very tangible way, which made an Engineering undergraduate degree the best option for me.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Falling in love with the subject material
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making someone else's life better in a very material sense
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Making enough money to support myself, pursue my dreams, and repay my family

EngrMotivation: Engineering is a degree in problem solving that can be applied in man ways which opens up many doors for my future. In addition, it involves STEM an area that I enjoy exploring and learning within. Finally, it teaches a way of thinking, espcially through courses such as, Praxis that can be useful in the real world by developing my character, mkaing me a better student adn in the future an employee.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Doing well by myself and my family
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Learning
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: The excitment of the future

EngrMotivation: I chose to pursue a degree in engineering as I have always admired students and professionals in academia. A higher education is something that I have always believed to be a lifelong accomplishments. But choosing engineering specifically, was a choice I made out of a desire to help others. Whether it be building a new bridge to connect two communities or designing a new computer to shape the way that the healthcare industry operates, ideas like this have given me a drive to learn more. A skillset acquired from degrees mentioned above such as music or literature, would not suffice for me. The application of material learned in the classroom to solving real-life problems is fascinating to me and has lead me to enter into a program to enable me to do the forementioned.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Helping people and communities.
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Using and learning math and computing.
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Working a job where I am constantly being challenged.

EngrMotivation:
In choosing an undergraduate degree in engineering, I hope to gain the tools necessary to solve difficult problems. Engineering is one of the few paths through which a small group of individuals can positively affect the lives of many, as exemplified by projects such as the hand-powered blood centrifuge developed by a Stanford professor. Also, my interests and aptitudes are suited most strongly to engineering rather than other methods of creating change such as politics or business. Specifically, my fascination with science, math, and design as well as my logical problem-solving style fits well with engineering, while my relatively reserved personality does not lend itself to influencing others through politics and business.

Besides the somewhat lofty motivation listed above, I also greatly enjoy the process of learning about the world and designing solutions to problems. Simply put, engineering is one of the most fun activities that I have participated in, from learning from my father the way circuits worked to building robots for various competitions. While I do want to use engineering as a way to make an impact in the world, I would not have chosen it if I did not think that I would enjoy it the way that I do.

Finally, I also chose engineering as a way to develop myself into a well-rounded person. I think that by taking a variety of courses and applying them to real life, I will become someone with a wide range of expertise and experience to draw on.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Feeding my desire to learn, create, and solve problems
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Creating positive change in people's lives
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Becoming a well-rounded, useful, and capable person

EngrMotivation: I chose Engineering because I was originally was planning on completing a Mathematics-Chemistry double major, but I decided that I would do better to challenge myself and increase my marketability in the job market later in life by having completed design and practical thinking courses (as opposed to courses that were all theory-based). I chose the university path over all others because I have always loved learning esoteric new ideas and challenging myself, opportunities which were not provided by paths other than university.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: learning new concepts
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: helping improve the lives of others
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: competition

EngrMotivation: Although I have other interests such as the arts, I personally felt that engineering was characteristically perfect as it allowed me to be creative while studying math and science under a profession with greater financial stability.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Feeling fulfilled +/ meaningful in my profession
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making change in the world for the better
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Making money to support myself and help my family

DontCallJusticiation: I am not the most confident person and I get anxious when I am called on. I don't want to embarrass myself in front of a lot of people.
EngrMotivation: I chose engineering because I liked my math and science courses in high school. Engineering also gives me the opportunity to help others. It is also not all theory and can actually be applied to problems found outside of school. To add, engineering is known to be a hard program and I wanted a challenge.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Being able to have a positive lasting impact on others
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making my friends and family proud
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Accomplishing something I did not think I could do

EngrMotivation: I was motivated by a curriculum that focused more broadly on the theoretical concepts as opposed to solely on practical applications. I see academics as more than a means to a profession and rather as a method of self improvement. I do however still enjoy applying the knowledge I've learned and that is why I have found a more healthy balance in Engineering science as opposed to a solely pure science.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: A future where I can hopefully create a lasting impact on society
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Creating a respected body of work that I am proud of
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Avoiding any future regrets

DontCallJusticiation: If I wish to participate, I will do so, otherwise, I would prefer not to be called on as I would not contribute anything resourceful.
EngrMotivation: There were several motivating factors that compelled me to pursue an undergraduate degree in engineering. My interest in mathematics, as well as the prestige of an engineering degree, were the driving factors that led me to choose this path. Additionally, the lifestyle of an engineer and being at the forefront of research and innovation had great appeal to me.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Accomplishments, Achievements, Recognition
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Family
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Personal Fulfillment

EngrMotivation: I am a person who loves to leave a positive impact on my community. In my opinion, a most impressive impact can be achieved through the optimization of scientific discoveries and theories to society's advantage. Finding practical use for new and fascinating science has been my goal since I was young and I think engineering will help me achieve that goal.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: The passion for complex and thought provoking details of science and mathematics
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: The thought of being able to use my knowledge to improve upon humanity
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Being confident in my abilities and knowing that I am such a trooper

DontCallJusticiation: As a person who did not take any AP, IB or any higher-level classes in high school, I feel as though I am coming into this program with less knowledge than others. Although this program builds the foundations from the bottom up, many of my peers I have had a chance to speak to already have programming experience, know integration, etc. Being called upon in class would make me feel self-conscious about my answers and my responses to questions in class because I fear any negative judgement from my peers.
EngrMotivation: I chose engineering because I realized how broad the field of engineering is and how the industry requires a large variety of skills. I believe that I have a decent set of soft skills (e.g: leadership, communication, etc.) and wanted to go to university to develop the theoretical and practical portion of the engineering skillset. The engineering program would allow me to practice the mathematics and science that I enjoy, but also allow me to exercise good communication and teamwork skills that I enjoy. As well, since engineering is such a broad field, I feel comfortable with the ability to explore other options within the diverse field of engineering in order to find something that I truly enjoy.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Feeling successful and being happy with my decisions
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making my family (and myself) proud of my achievements
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Feeling financially secure

EngrMotivation: For me personally, I have always been passionate about space and space travel. Being an engineer, specifically in Engineering Science (with a major in Aero) would enable me to follow this dream and literally reach for the stars. In any other program, I feel that this drive for something bigger will never be satisfied and I will be left regretting my decisions. I also picked engineering as I was looking for an academic challenge that can push me out of my comfort zone and to deal with major failure for the first time in life. I want to be in an environment where my decisions and actions can be fairly critiqued such that I may learn from my mistakes. I feel as if I was babied in high school, I want to be put in a realistic environment that will ultimately help me become a better person.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Following my dream of being a rocket scientist
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Being a part of something bigger than myself
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Making enough money that I can provide a comfortable life for my family (down the road)

HomeCity[comment]: May return to (R)ichmond Hill on weekends.
EngrMotivation: I often stick to an idea or interest I believe that is right and meaningful, and I make decisions and actions based on it as the motivation. In this case, I chose this undergraduate degree in Engineering because it will allow me to use my creativity to design aerial vehicles in my job, which I consider as the most beneficial combination of a hobby and a career to me and society.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Becoming an aerospace engineer, who designs planes or rockets.
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Expressing my creativity in my designs and works.
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Having a meaningful and happy life while benefiting the world.

DontCallJusticiation: Coming up with answers on the spot in front of a large crowd makes me anxious.
EngrMotivation: I think pursuing an undergraduate degree in engineering is the most versatile option available because of its broad scope and applications in many different fields. The engineering science program in particular prioritizes an interdisciplinary approach which I value highly because I wish to experience a wide variety of fields and topics before specializing eventually. As well, I enjoy math and science courses more than others in high school and growing up in a family of all engineers, I am familiar and comfortable with the life and work of an engineer.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Being self-satisfied
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making my parents proud
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Improving the world

EngrMotivation: Ever since a young age, engineering has deeply interested me and been one of my passions. Having grown up with my father as an engineer (and an EngSci graduate), engineering has always been presented  to me as an ideal career, being a combination of maths, sciences, innovation, and creativity. Engineering also allows for someone to easily go into entrepreneurship, something which I am very interested in. It also prepares people for solving complex problems. Additionally, it is no secret that engineers make a fair bit of money at the end of the day.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Discovering/learning new and interesting things
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Helping people through the creation and advancement of technology
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Being able to solve problems I am invested in

EngrMotivation: Ever since I was a kid, I've wanted to be an inventor. Being able to make a significant difference for the better in even just the lives of a few through the optimization of current systems or devices, but preferably with the creation of something brand new is very appealing to me. With this in mind, I discerned that engineering science would be the best fit for me.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Chances of getting a job I enjoy
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Opportunity to challenge myself in a field I enjoy
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Opportunity to meet like-minded individuals

EngrMotivation: I decided to pursue an undergraduate degree in Engineering over other viable paths and programs because I have always been interested in math and science and how they can be applied to the world around us. The reason why I chose Engineering over the Science programs was because I realized that an Engineering degree would give me a better chance at obtaining a decent job with decent wage. After conducting some research, I realized that science degrees will not help you in employment unless you have done some post-grad work or are looking for a job in academia. I specifically chose Engineering Science because I believed that it was the silver lining between both programs, Engineering and Science. Through it I hope to learn some of the theory behind the concepts engineers learn as well as have the opportunity to apply this knowledge in our world.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: I want to become a more confident, well-rounded, and compassionate person that is able to help those around me. I want to become a person that I can be proud of.
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: I want to make enough money that I am able to live a life of relative comfort, pursue my goals, and to take care of my family.
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: I want to experience more of life (traveling, living in different cultures, exposing myself to new things)

EngrMotivation: The main reason I chose an undergraduate degree in Engineering was to avoid limiting my future options. As I am extremely indecisive, I definitely didn't have a clear enough idea of what I want to do to attempt anything related to entrepreneurship, and even college seemed to be too restricting, both because less positions are open to college graduates than university graduates and because college would only have been 2 years rather than 4 (or 5 with PEY). Still on the same idea of indecision, I have always loved math and physics, but I am also interested in some of the social sciences that examine more of a human interaction and policy aspect, such as law or international relations. I had briefly considered engineering, but honestly thought it was nothing more than building bridges, buildings and cars and programming computers. These first options simply didn't interest me, and the last one is something I know absolutely nothing about, so I was worried about trying to build a career out of it. However, out of a lack of knowledge of what else to do with math and physics, I applied to engineering anyways. After this, I got to know more about the different aspects of it through the university's various applicant events and information sessions. This really helped make my decision, because that's where I realized that an engineering degree is actually applicable to so many different fields and careers due to the transferable nature of all the soft skills that are essential whether I decide to pursue law, a master's degree in engineering, a career in research, or really anything else.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Succeeding at reaching personal goals I have set for myself, regardless of how that compares to the rest of the group (I am not a competitive person by nature, but enjoy pushing myself to both learn new skills and improve ones I learned a while ago)
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Obtaining a job that will allow me to travel, whether for work itself or thanks to a decent salary and amount of vacation time
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Making my family proud of everything I've managed to do with their support

EngrMotivation: I am very interested in the world of design and how the design of everything around us effects everyone's daily lives. I also very much enjoyed learning and practising maths, sciences and quantitative courses. Engineering is a great fit with good employment opportunities fitting these areas of study.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Pursuing a career incorporating design
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Utilizing maths and science in my career
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Making enough money to pursue my dreams

EngrMotivation: I chose to pursue an undergraduate degree in Engineering because I'm interested in math and science. I'm really interested in learning about math and physics, and so I chose EngSci because I felt that I would be able to explore and broaden my interests in this program. In addition, I chose an engineering program, over a pure math/science program, because it is a better guarantee for employment (I've heard that you can easily find a job with an engineering degree, but a B.Sc. usually requires graduate school or professional studies in order to find a good job). Furthermore, I'm really interested in the theoretical aspect of math and physics, and so I chose EngSci because this program focuses heavily on theory, as opposed to just practical/Engineering-related skills (which I'm also interested in learning about as well). An engineering program would also allow me to gain many useful communication, professional, and practical skills, which will be useful regardless of whatever field I intend to pursue in the future (a science degree would focus less on these skills). Lastly, I chose EngSci over other engineering programs because of its flexibility and depth.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Knowing and discovering things that few other people do
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Getting a respected and meaningful job
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Being able to make a positive difference in the world around me

EngrMotivation: In all honesty, I was looking forward to entering a science program with a focus in physics and astronomy, but what really captivated my interest is the breadth offered by an engineering program. I view being an engineer as a professional who has a wealth of information in various topics and being able to apply their skills in versatile manners. And that's probably the biggest attraction for me. There is not one industry or branch of the workforce where an engineer is not required. This ability is like no other.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: My pursuit of knowledge
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Achieve my dreams and passions
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Being able to take care of my family in the future

GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Making enough money

GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Accomplishing my dream of working with planes.
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Making money to repay my parents and to support myself.
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Being a proud Engsci student and feeling others' admiration.

EngrMotivation: I originate from a culture that places heavy emphasis on education and learning. It was never out of the question that I would be attending university. I chose engineering mostly because of my fascination with Physics and my love for Mathematics, not to mention a little cultural pressure here and there
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Changing the world
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Being a distinct individual in society
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Personal satisfaction and fulfillment

EngrMotivation: I chose engineering over other because to me engineering means innovation, and innovation is the future, and I would really like to be part of the people that leads humanity into the future. I also chose engineering because it opens countless doors filled with opportunities. From designing rockets to investment banking, engineers are in almost every sector if the world.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: To live a life of such value that it changes the path of humanity in a positive way
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: To be someone people look up to and gain motivation from themselves
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: To remembered in history as a person who contributed immensely to the human civilization

EngrMotivation: I chose engineering because I believe that the future needs intelligent yet innovative minds to help improve the lifestyle of humans and solve the problems as our world becomes larger and more crowded. Engineering programs will provide me with the theoretical knowledge and practical skills to be able to learn the techniques and concepts for the future. Undergraduate is the path I chose because I believe it challenges my learning style and will push me to adapt to a more effective way of learning. In addition, possessing an undergraduate degree will be a way where I can prove to others that I have the skillset to do bigger things. It will also serve as a way to meet other like-minded people to network and make friends.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Making positive impact on the life of others
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Achieving success  in my passion for engineering
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Providing for my family and friends financially

DontCallJusticiation:
I am more than happy to express my opinions in a small group, or with people I trust, and often find myself sharing an opinion with the person beside me; however, I try to be eloquent and concise in my expression and often in a big group I feel that my point is lost. 
I often provide an "out" at the end of my argument, like a crutch protecting myself. 
*If called upon directly, provided I am following and not super lost/out of my element, I can present to a group. My presentation skills are actually rather good, I just prefer to self-determine when my feedback is necessary.
EngrMotivation: I moved past other math and science programs (actuarial science, math, Bsci in physics) fro employment stability and an increased technical background, though I have never really "been an engineer" ie. I've never coded, or invented etc. I picked EngSci for the math/stats/finance option, although I am considering physics and entering the academic field. I've always been very academic and this seemed like a good foundation for anything I decided to pursue in the future, even if I don't work as a typical engineer.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Wanting to achieve/live up to expectations
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: making a difference/leaving a mark
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: being successful to maintain a good lifestyle

EngrMotivation: I chose an undergraduate degree in Engineering because the program closely resonates with my goals and values. For instance, I enjoy helping people (on large scales) and engineering is what allows for innovative change to take place; thus, creating better lives for an immense number of people. There are a wide variety of problems present across the world; such as, extreme weather conditions due to climate change, scarce resources, and record-low scientific literacy levels, etc. Thus, engineers must come up with creative solutions that create better lives for everyone. Moving on, I chose Engineering because I want to be a part of the teams of people who are coming up with resolutions that have never been previously pondered by any known person.
