I chose engineering because of its adaptable nature; I have known engineers who have gone to work in a variety of fields such as business, law, medicine and  forms of engineering which they did not complete their undergraduate degrees in. I am interested in the idea of learning the engineering 'mindset' which would help me to achieve my goal in multiple ways, regardless of which specific technical skills I learn. I was also very interested in majoring in psychology yet I chose engineering because of its adaptable nature. In addition, engineering still allows me to work with people, for people and a good understanding of humanities is required to understand how to really improve society.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: I want to understand myself and what interests me by trying everything that I can
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: A stable and secure future in which I can provide basic needs for myself and family
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Getting the most out of University (To justify tuition costs)

EngrMotivation: I chose to pursue engineering due to my exposure to the field on a First Robotics Team in high school. I greatly enjoyed the experience of working in a team to accomplish a design goal in a very short period of time. I have fairly strong skills in chemistry, physics and math and hence felt like my skills supported my interest in engineering from robotics. While I have wavered at points (most notably while working as an intern at a tech company which had similar aspects to an engineering job and I found that I didn't love the internship), I have since realised that I really value the teamwork aspect. Working alone is simply not as interesting to me and I don't feel as much pressure to deliver, so it's reassuring that normally engineers work in some sort of team. I also chose to pursue engineering due to my parents both doing their degrees as engineers, so it's been the "safe choice" for me for quite some time. Regardless, I definitely valued the ability to work across a range of high performing fields with engineering science specifically, compared to the confines of many ArtSci degrees and even other engineering schools.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Successfully completing a team project with people who I would count as friends.
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Using engineering to travel and help others worldwide
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: The ability to have a solid base (job/income) on which to try new things (activities/volunteering/personal things) from

Other alternatives such as music and literature will still remain important in my personal life, but separate from my professional life.

Mastering this wide variety of skill would allow me to extend my future career to different job sectors (like entrepreneurship and the medical industry), while accommodating my current inability to choose a specific field. The ability to teach me essential skills while accommodating my current unstable decision, convinced me that the immense workload would be worth it. I believe that I will discover the proper path, leading towards my ultimate goal, through the Engineering program, since it is the only program that validates my vague wish to "improve" the world.

EngrMotivation:
My introduction to Engineering started from the FIRST Robotics program, which inspired me to pursue engineering. I have participated in the program for four years, and despite being relatively introverted and shy, made many friends and had a great time participating in it. This inspired me to pursue engineering. In grade 11, I had discovered another thing that interested me greatly, which was physics. I wasn't necessarily the strongest physics or math student, but seeing mathematics explain the world seemed fantastic to me. After doing an essay on terminal velocity, I had greater respect for math as an analytical tool. Ultimately, this led me to pursue engineering science over a physics degree or a normal engineering degree, due to the combination of science and engineering.

I also found engineering science's breadth requirements appealing. I think learning a lot is important in today's age. A lot of engineering solutions now require mechanical, electrical, computer, etc knowledge to develop something. Robots are a good example of this. This inspired me to choose engineering science over ECE since I wanted to get a bigger picture view of how these complex systems, and the fundamental principles behind them (i.e. the science).

Another thing that made me choose engineering over physics was employment prospects. I don't think I wanted to pursue a pHD, and I was confident I wasn't genius level in it, so I decided that getting an engineering degree was safer than a physics degree. The harder maths also worries me since I'm not particularly strong at the proof aspects of math. I chose engineering over computer science because I still wanted to get a physical background, and learn a lot about a variety of fields, which I felt engineering did better over computer science. 

I chose engineering over other career pathways because as I've mentioned before, I wanted to learn the underlying theory of many principles and create tools used by people, rather than just use tools. I also felt that an engineering degree would help me pursue research to help people or entrepreneurship (in the tech industry) should I desire to do that.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Learning a lot
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Meeting people who can change the way I think and inspire me
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Getting involved in interesting projects (i.e. the various design teams at UofT)

EngrMotivation: To be quite honest, my greatest passion lies in the fields of Philosophy and Religion, more specifically Philosophy of Religion and Epistemology (and maybe a little bit of metaphysics too). However, a close second is the fields of Mathematics, Physics, and Chemistry, and an undergraduate degree in Engineering, if I am able to complete it and/or don't decide to switch out, provides me with a practical degree that opens up a wide range of fields that I can apply these concepts, something I can't do with many other degrees, especially those fields I am interested in. This is the primary motivation for my choice, and perhaps I might not go through with it. But I am confident that gaining the practical experience and the flexibility that an undergraduate degree in engineering provides (and that I have seen many times in my personal relationships with engineers) would never be detrimental to me, either from a personal development POV, or a financial security POV. Overall, there's not many downsides, besides working 24/7, but many upsides that I am personally interested in.

GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: To be the best I can be and always try my best, no matter what.
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: To give back to my family for all the opportunities I have been allotted through them.

DontCallJusticiation: When put under pressure to answer a question publicly, I tend to lose sight of the finer points of the question, and my answers tend to become less creative and interesting. In other words, because I'm not a fast thinker, I  need  time to come up with good ideas, and for this reason I  believe that being called upon to answer a question in class might result in my answer not being as good as I would like.
EngrMotivation: I feel as through engineering  I will be able to satisfy two cravings that are seemingly at odds with each other.  The first is a desire to gain a conceptual understanding of the world, and the second is to remain within the realm of practicality. I am a fairly imaginative person, and my head is often in the clouds thinking about  new ways of contextualizing my experiential knowledge into a wider scheme, with the goal of eventually being able to use it to make accurate predictions about the world. I believe the path of engineering is very suitable for me in this way, since that same goal seems to be the motif of the engineering community as a whole.
GeneralMotivations[MOST]: Changing the world for the better
GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Becoming a good role model

EngrMotivation: Engineering Science covers a wide array of options one could choose from. I was merely attracted to the idea of learning and working hard every day. As weird as it sounds, I get a rewarding feeling when I finish studying even if it is late at night. In all truthfulness, I could have gone for either visual arts or mathematics; however, I was afraid that I would get too bored in those areas, so I picked a program that is not just challenging, but can also cover areas that I am generally good and not good at. I also quit my job as soon as I entered the program because I wanted to give all my focus to this program. One thing I also really like is the idea of competitiveness. I like to be competitive, and I like to win. Whenever I would lose, I would get very motivated to win. These are the reasons why I chose Engineering Science.

EngrMotivation: Throughout high school, I found no interest in any particular group of subject until twelfth grade. I thoroughly enjoyed my physics class because they taught all the concepts through an experimental manner. For a while I thought I wanted to go into physics, but after quantum and relativity I realized I liked the physics that I could see and touch. This field of physics is engineering. While I have no prior engineering experience, I'm interesting in learning the various applications of physics and how mathematical expressions can describe and predict the real world.

GeneralMotivations[SECOND]: Repaying back my family
GeneralMotivations[THIRD]: Having fun

EngrMotivation: I have many different interests, including math, science, and technology, and this program combines them all into a challenging and practical package. I chose to pursue a degree because of the doors it opens in the future, especially in the engineering field.
